"Fun" fact: They only banned the use of DDT in the U.S. in 1972. It was still produced in the U.S. and sold and used in other countries at least until 1985. And, though several other countries also banned it, there wasn't an official worldwide ban (ratified by 170 countries) until 2004. Despite the ban, some countries, most notably India and N. Korea, still use it for crops.

There's also an exemption that allows its use for the public health as a disease vector control. For example, parts of Africa where malaria and other such ailments is still very prevalent use DDT, however, in this case they line the insides of walls with it to deter insects like mosquitoes from getting in.
